gton, Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hatch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."],"variants":[{"name":"Hedge","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a hedge or enclosure, from Middle English <i>hegge</i> ‘hedge, fence’. In the early Middle Ages, hedges were not merely dividers between fields, but had an important defensive function when planted around a settlement or enclosure.","English: probably also a variant of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."]},{"name":"Hatcher","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."]}]},{"name":"Jeffery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffry","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":21,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jeffery de Hatch was born in 1238, in Arlington, Devon, England, his father, Jeffery de Hatche, was 26 and his mother, De Hatche, was 26. He married Claris de Aller in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1276, in his hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1238–1276":"1238–1276","1240–M